{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488703"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:52:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:52:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"510"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/510"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.82,0.01,0.04,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"510"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101877"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/510"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"510"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84333"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"432"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"143"},{"type":"contributions","id":"179"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35316"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101877"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents with a one hour history of sudden onset vision loss in the right eye which he describes as cobwebs suddenly covering his vision. He was diagnosed with type 2 diabetes over ten years ago and was recently started on insulin due to poor glycaemic control on other medications. He also suffers from hypertension, but has no other medical conditions. His visual acuity is 6/12 in the left eye and hand motion in the right.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to determine the underlying cause of the current problem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Slit lamp illumination","Fundoscopy","Visual fields testing","Tonometry","Pinhole testing"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven the man has poorly controlled diabetes and his presentation of sudden onset \u0022cobwebs\u0022 obscuring vision, it is likely that he is suffering from a dense vitreous haemorrhage secondary to neovascularisation of the retina. Additionally, given he has vascular risk factors [diabetes mellitus Type 2 and hypertension] he is at risk for other causes of sudden vision loss including a central retinal artery occlusion, central retinal vein occlusion and hypertensive retinopathy. A \u003Cstrong\u003Efundoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E would clearly identify pathology affecting the vitreous, retina or optic nerve accounting for the presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESlit lamp illumination is useful in investigating many causes of vision loss and in the setting of a vitreous hemorrhage may demonstrate red blood cells in the anterior vitreous. However, fundoscopy will allow direct visualisation of the vitreous haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVisual fields testing will demonstrate the known loss of vision but has low diagnostic value compared to fundoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETonometry is used to measure intraocular pressure, and may be helpful in diagnosing conditions such as glaucoma. Given this patient\u0027s history and risk factors, tonometry provides minimal diagnostic value.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPinhole testing is predominantly used to assess for refractive error when measuring visual acuity. Since both diabetes and hypertension cause a retinal pathology rather than a refractive one, this is unlikely to be helpful.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fundoscopy is the appropriate investigation for suspected retinal problems."],"references":["Frank RN. Diabetic retinopathy. N Engl J Med. 2004 Jan 1;350(1):48-58. doi: 10.1056/NEJMra021678. PMID: 14702427.","Ehlers JP, Shah CP. The Wills eye manual: Office and emergency room diagnosis and treatment of eye disease. Philadelphia: Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2016"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84333"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"510"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84333","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84333"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-04T20:31:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-04T20:33:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"510"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101877"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGro